{
  "text": "First, we define the parity sequence of f to be {p 0 , p 1 , p 2 , . . .}, where p k = (T k (f ))(0). That is, p k is the constant term of T k (f ), which indicates whether tT k+1 (f ) = mT k (f ) + 1 or tT k+1 (f ) = T k (f ). To prove Theorem 2.2, we follow the outline used by Everett [CITATION_1] to prove the corresponding result for the 3x + 1 system in Z. We prove that the parity sequence of a uniformly-chosen polynomial in F 2 [t] is uniformly distributed in the set of sequences in {0, 1}. Then we prove that almost all such sequences correspond to polynomials with finite stopping time.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "122111722"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "122111722": {
      "title": "Iteration of the number-theoretic function f (2n) = n, f (2n + 1) = 3n + 2",
      "abstract": "It is a long-standing conjecture that, under iteration of the number-theoretic function, ::: f(2n)=n,f(2n + 1) = 3n + 2 ::: ::: ::: every integer m has an iterate fk(m) = 1. Since virtually nothing is known about the question, save that it seems to be true for m up to the millions, it may be of interest to know that almost every m has an iterate fk(m) <m, a result proved in the present report."
    }
  }
}